  footnotes: []
english:
  title: The Hall
  author: An Jin
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I return from the east, my seat still warm,
    Yet north again I must depart, my ambitions stretch far.
    The parting horse tosses its head with eagerness,
    While my beloved's heart breaks in silent anguish.

    Through clouds I glimpse the royal court,
    Beyond the heavens I see my ancestral hall.
    Though youth grants me wealth and standing,
    I must remember—duty to parents calls, morning and evening.
  footnotes:
    - The 'parting horse' and 'beloved' suggest the speaker is torn between pursuing official ambitions (traveling north) and familial obligations and romantic ties (returning home to the east).
    - The 'ancestral hall' (훤당) represents both family heritage and filial duty, contrasted with the speaker's pursuit of official position and 'wealth and standing.'
    - The final couplet emphasizes the Confucian virtue of filial piety (정성), suggesting that despite youth and ambition, one must not neglect the duty of serving and caring for one's parents.
